04246nam a22005055i 9781554582020DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20102010xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97815545820207 a10.51644/97815545820202doi  a(DE-B1597)667508  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1029.5b.K23 2010eb 7aPOL0110102bisacsh04a327.7105694/090462221 aKay, Zachariah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Diplomacy of Impartiality :bCanada and Israel, 1958-1968 /cZachariah Kay. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (138 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tNote on Sources -- tIntroduction -- tThe Diefenbaker Regnum -- tPlus ça change, plus c’est la même chose -- tDiefenbaker’s Helmsmanship -- tCaution in a Nuclear Minefield -- tThe Pearson Era -- tThe Pearson Primeministership -- tCommons and Crisis: A Case Study -- tWar and a Wary Ottawa -- tPost Conflict and Compromise -- tClosing the Pearson Era -- tSummary and Conclusions -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Diplomacy of Impartiality is an analysis of a major decade in Canadian–Israeli relations, dealing with significant events that led to the Six-Day War of 1967 and its aftermath. Using primary documentation from the National Archives of Canada and the Israeli State Archives, Zachariah Kay shows that although Canada was committed to Israel’s existence, its foreign policy was governed by the scrupulous impartiality that had become a principle guideline when dealing with Israel and the Middle East. The first section of the book deals with the Progressive Conservative government headed by John Diefenbaker in the first part of the decade and his Israeli counterpart, David Ben Gurion. The second section considers the latter part of the decade, with reference to Lester Pearson’s Liberal government and the Israeli prime minister Levi Eshkol. The book shows that in spite of political differences between the leaders and their parties, the Canadian bureaucracy maintained a policy of impartiality, following the lines of non-commitment and prudence practiced prior to the re-establishment of Jewish sovereignty in Palestine with the State of Israel. Issues such as the Arab–Israeli conflict, nuclear power, governments and parliaments, and the pre- and post-Six-Day War are dealt with in detail. The assessed evidence proves that impartiality as a quasi-bureaucratic ordinance kept Canada on the path it maintained in subsequent decades into the twenty-first century. The Diplomacy of Impartiality provides an essential understanding of events surrounding today’s Canadian relationship with Israel and the Arab–Israeli conflict.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Diplomacy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721940uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978155458202040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781554582020423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781554582020/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010c2010d2011  aGBV-deGruyter-alles